b'[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe3322.htm)  [Next](sbe3324.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/817536033X/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Minor Law Books (SBE33)_ , by Julius Jolly, [1889], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n#### 16\\. Valid Evidence.\n\n229. 229 Where there is conflicting evidence, the plurality of witnesses decides the matter. If the number of witnesses is equal (on both sides), the testimony of those must be accepted as correct,\n\np. 96\n\nwhose veracity is not liable to suspicion. If the number of such witnesses is\nequal (on both sides) (the testimony of these must be accepted), who are\npossessed of a superior memory.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[95:229](sbe3323.htm#fr_281) Manu VIII, 73; Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya II, 78; Vish\n_n_ u VIII, 39.\n\n229, 230. Where witnesses endowed with a good memory are found on both sides\nin equal numbers, evidence based on recollection is incapable of influencing\nthe decision of the suit. The witnesses must not be examined, and the above\nrule comes into force, that the witnesses become incompetent, because they do\nnot agree with one another. A. See par. 261.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 17. Invalid Evidence](sbe3324.htm)\n\n'